 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are tasked with classifying a given piece of user text input into exactly ONE of the following functional domain categories:\n\nalarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS:\n\n1. **Input Format:** You will be given a block of text that represents a user's spoken or typed request. Only the “text” content is relevant for classification.\n\n2. **Primary Intent:** Carefully read the full user input and determine its *primary functional intent*. Focus on what the user is fundamentally asking the assistant to do. Do not rely only on individual keywords; interpret the meaning in context, considering conversational nuances and usual assistant usage.\n\n3. **Category Selection:** Assign the single *most specific and appropriate* category from the list. The category must match the function the user is requesting. Review the detailed rules below, especially regarding boundary cases between similar categories:\n\n   - **Alarm- and Calendar-related:**\n     - Choose 'alarm_set' ONLY for requests to set a basic alarm to trigger at a certain time or after a set duration (e.g., “Set an alarm for 6 AM”). If the request involves reminders or events tied to specific times/dates or involves a note or reminder content (e.g., “remind me to call mom Friday at noon” or “make a note to pay the bill and remind me on Saturday at 9am”), select 'calendar_set' instead.\n     - 'alarm_query' is for user requests about existing or pending alarms.\n     - 'calendar_set' is for adding/reminding/creating *events or reminders* about real-world actions at or for specific times or dates (including adding notes or reminders; these belong to the calendar domain, not the lists or alarms domain).\n     - 'calendar_query' is for asking about scheduled events or availability.\n     - 'calendar_remove' is for deleting or canceling events/reminders.\n\n   - **Lists and Notes:**\n     - 'lists_createoradd' is for adding items to lists or creating new lists (e.g., “add milk to my shopping list”). \n     - If the intent is to remind about an action at a specific time, do NOT select 'lists_createoradd'—choose 'calendar_set'.\n     - 'lists_query' is for viewing/listing items in lists.\n     - 'lists_remove' is for removing items from lists.\n\n   - **Weather:**\n     - Any request involving weather, outdoor conditions, forecasts, temperatures, or alerts/notifications tied to changing environmental/weather conditions (even if phrased like an alarm or alert) must be classified as 'weather_query'.\n\n   - **Entertainment:**\n     - 'play_music' is for requests to play music or musical content.\n     - 'play_radio' is for requests to play radio stations, broadcast shows, or radio-like entertainment (including music-based shows).\n     - 'music_query' is for queries *about* music without playback.\n     - 'play_audiobook' and 'play_podcasts' as named.\n     - 'news_query' for asking for news.\n\n   - **Email:**\n     - 'email_sendemail' is for sending or composing new emails.\n     - 'email_query' is for checking emails or asking about existing emails.\n\n   - **Other Functional Areas:**\n     - 'cooking_recipe' for recipe/instruction requests.\n     - 'datetime_query' for current date, time, or calendar conversions.\n     - 'iot_hue_lightoff' for controlling (usually turning off) smart lights.\n     - 'takeaway_order' for ordering food for pick-up or takeout.\n     - 'transport_query' for directions, routes, transportation options.\n\n   - **Recommendations:**\n     - 'recommendation_events' is for suggestions about events to attend.\n     - 'recommendation_locations' is for suggestions about places to visit or go.\n\n   - **Social/Media:**\n     - 'social_post' is for requests to post or share something on social media or to get/post community or group updates.\n     - Notably, when asked about \"customer service feedback,\" the primary intent is to interact with customer reviews/social input, so classify as 'social_post', NOT as a factoid Q&A.\n\n   - **Question Answering (QA):**\n     - 'qa_currency' is only for queries about currency rates/exchange.\n     - 'qa_definition' for defining words, phrases, or concepts.\n     - 'qa_factoid' for questions seeking general factual answers (dates, names, facts).\n     - 'qa_stock' for stock prices or financial instruments.\n\n   - **General/Fun/Other:**\n     - 'general_quirky' for playful, fun, or oddball requests that don’t fit anywhere else.\n\n4. **Critical Rules:**\n   - If a request covers both list/note and calendar/event aspects (e.g., “make a note to pay the bill and remind me Saturday at 9am”), always prioritize *calendar_set* if any part involves scheduling or timed reminders.\n   - For “alert me when the outside temperature reaches X” and similar, always use 'weather_query', even if “alert” might suggest an alarm.\n   - For social platform or community interaction (“what is the customer service feedback”), prefer 'social_post' over 'qa_factoid', as the user is looking for social or review content.\n\n5. **Response Format:**\n   - Output ONLY the exact single label from the list above. Do NOT provide explanations, context, or additional information.\n   - Never output multiple labels or anything not in the predefined list.\n\nFollow all provided rules and detailed category boundaries strictly. Pay special attention to ambiguous cases, and always choose the *most specific* functional domain appropriate to the request."
 },
